ominate candidates for\nPresident and Vice President of the\nUnited States and to transact such\nother and further business as may\nproperly come before the said Con\nvention.\nIt is Further Resplved, That the\nbasis of representation at the State\nConvention above provided for shall\nbe .two from jeach county\nand one delegate {or each fifty votes\ncast for the average vote in each\ncounty for the Democratic candi\ndates for judges of the Supreme\nCourt for the state of Washington at\nthe election held Noveiyber 6, 1906,\nin said state and the major fraction\ntliereoi; the various counties In this\ncall oeing entitled to the number of\ndelegates as follows:\nAdams 1 (Lewis g. 22\nAsotin SLincoln 21\nBenton SMason 6\nChehalis 2GOkanogan 14\nChelan 11 Pacific 9\nClallam SPierce 4#\nClarke 12San Juan 3\nColumbia 13Skagit' .._ .20\nCowlitz 12Skamania 3\nDouglas lOSnohomlsh ....So\nFerry OSpokane 73\nFranklin SStevens ..26\nGarfield SThurston 17\nIsland 3Wankiakum 4\nJefferson GWalla Walla ..23\nKing 97Whatcom 2S\nKitsap .Whitman 39\nKittitas 15Yaklma 2S\nKlickitat 9\nTotal 697\nA. R. TIT LOW, Chairman.\nAttest:\nCARL D. ESHELMAN, Secretary.\nIN THE POLICE COURT.\nJudge Loomis is Still Doing a Thriv\ning business at Ihc Old Stand.\nFourteen esses of vagrancy and J). D's\nshowed up in toe police court Tuesday\nmorning, and were linn ted the usual $10\nr t\nor ten days, with a ihance to leave town\non a 'unpen led sentence.\nM. Kaufman, one of the alleged viola-'\ntors nf the fit inlay law.-failed to answer\nroll call, and his bail of $85 was declared\nforfeited.\nM. 11. Wilson was called upon to ex\nplain hia reasons for carrying a concealed\nweapon, which he did by sajing he was\nIliad to no to Cosmopoln unai tiled.\nAfter Iving admonished of ttiedinger\nin ibis practice. Wilson was allowed to\nhis way\u2014to sin no more.\nVest*rday morning, four appeared be\nfore the desk, against whose names ap-j\npe.ired the charge of disorderly conduct,\nand nil got the $10 with the usual al\nternative of hoarding it out.\nMr. and Mrs. l'eter Hanson were dis\ncharged yeiterday on the charge pr\u00ab i\nfeied by the truant otlicer, of their f\ndaughter not attending school, upon a!\npromise to send the child to school to- j\nday. The Hanson's feel that they have\nbeen made ttie object of a stringent con\nstruction of the law in this case. Their\ndaughter is but 14 years of age, and is in\nthe eighth grade \u2014proving that her edu\ncation has not been neglected\u2014but she\nwas transferred from the High school\nbuilding to the Frauklin school, which\nshe did not like, and her parents were\nabout to send tier to St. Hose academy.\nWhen the arrest was made, the girl had\nbeen but two days absent from school,\nand this morning she was enrolled in the\nacademy. This is the story of the pa\nrents, who have lived 16 years iu Aber\ndeen, and if true, shows a lack of dis\ncretion somewhere.\nJohn Peterson was put off a street car\nyesterday for failing to pay his fare, and\nto get even be threw a stone through a\nwindow of the car. He was given a fine\nof $25 or 25 days in jail, this morning, in\nthe police court. t\nJohn Hendricks was up this morning\non a disorderly charge, and drew $lo\nfine.\nTbe two casea against O. C. Vamrnen,\nfor violatien of the Sunday law, were set\n(or trial tomorrow.\nMaking toom fori Spring Merchandise# compels\nsalesgirl all departments\nspring! suits,\nnow on-displav. Paris and London have deeded.\nNew York has criticized, improved and adopted.\nThe fashions are absolutely defined.\n\"Butterfly Suits\"\nin Copenhagen, 'reseda, shades of brown, navy in\nPanamas, broadcloths, English series in plain as\nwell as fancy stripes and checks will be the proper\ntiling for spring l We have them from\n$15.00 TO $45.00\nFINAL CLEARING PRICES\nMILLINERY \u2014Your choice of any street hat\nvalue up to #2.50 now 75c each.\nHats up to 7.50 now #2.05\nHals up to 12.50 now 4.95\nHats up to 25.00 now 9.95\nFURS Children's Coats\nSome 